\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Our paper is based on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Precautionary Borrowing and the Credit Card Puzzle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by Druedahl and JÃ¸rgensen (2015).
 We have the equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}V(\boldsymbol{S}_{t}) & =\hspace{0.1cm}\max_{D_{t},C_{t}}\hspace{0.1cm}\frac{C_{t}^{1-\rho}-1}{1-\rho}+\beta\mathbb{E}[V(\boldsymbol{S}_{t+1})]\\
\text{s.t.}\\
W_{t} & =\left(1+r_{w}\right)W_{t-1}+Y_{t}-\underbrace{D_{t-1}(r_{d}+\lambda)}_{\text{Interest + installment}}+\underbrace{D_{t}-\left(1-\lambda\right)D_{t-1}}_{\text{New debt}}-C_{t}\\
N_{t} & =W_{t}-D_{t}\\
D_{t} & \leq\max\left\{ \underbrace{(1-\lambda)D_{t-1}}_{\text{Old contract}}\hspace{0.2cm},\hspace{0.2cm}\underbrace{\mathbf{1}_{x_{t}=0}\left(\eta\cdot N_{t}+\varphi\cdot P_{t}\right)}_{\text{New contract}}\right\} \\
W_{t},D_{t},C_{t} & \geq0
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 gauss-hermite quaditure shocks and income growth, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently, we solve the model by interpolating over a helper variable called
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{t+1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t}=\underset{M_{t}}{\underbrace{(1-r_{w})W_{t-1}+Y_{t}-(r_{d}+\lambda)D_{t-1}}}+D_{t}-(1-\lambda)D_{t-1}-C_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t}=M_{t}+D_{t}-(1-\lambda)D_{t-1}-C_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\leq M_{t}+D_{t}-(1-\lambda)D_{t-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{t+1}=(1-r_{w})W_{t}+Y_{t+1}-(r_{d}+\lambda)D_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal consumption, utility and debt at a given 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../../Documents/pasted3.png
	lyxscale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results seem reasonable since consumption and utility is growing with
 wealth, and low income households take on more debt.
 Defining the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

puzzle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 group as households that neither fully borrow or save, we get the following
 figure that is like figure 6.1 in the paper:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../../Documents/pasted2.png
	lyxscale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We talked about solving the model directly by interpolating over 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{t+1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{t+1}=(1-r_{w})W_{t}+Y_{t+1}-(r_{d}+\lambda)D_{t}+D_{t+1}-(1-\lambda)D_{t}-C_{t+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is one option better or more correct than the other?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we have two states and two choices, we interpolate over a 2d grid,
 where we use the package provided in the tools-module.
 How much theory should we include about 2d interpolation? Is it possible
 to use other kinds of 2d-interpolations such as B-splines?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper nests the model, so a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 only affects the debt choice.
 Is this nested VFI? And if so, is it needed to compute the post-decision
 states?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found it difficult to replicate results of the paper 1-to-1.
 Instead, we considered doing counterfactuals on model simulations instead.
 Are these results economically meaningful enough for the term paper?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

